---
import ProjectLayout from '../../layouts/ProjectLayout.astro';
const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL.replace(/\/$/, '');
---
<ProjectLayout
  title="Spatial Equity of Shared Micro-Mobility in Peripheral Neighborhoods"
  year="2023"
  category="Spatial Analysis · Urban Equity"
  tools={['Python', 'GeoPandas', 'SciPy', 'QGIS', 'Kernel Density Estimation', 'TAZ Analysis']}
>

  <section class="proj-section">
    <h2 class="proj-section-title">Overview</h2>
    <div class="proj-body">
      <p>
        Shared micro-mobility operators promised to extend accessible transportation beyond the city
        center. In practice, commercial incentives push vehicles toward high-density, high-demand zones —
        concentrating supply in central neighborhoods and leaving peripheral quarters underserved.
        This analysis investigated whether shared e-scooter availability was equitably distributed
        across Tel Aviv's outer quarters.
      </p>
      <p>
        Using vehicle location snapshots from multiple operators collected via the Populus platform,
        kernel density estimation (KDE) was applied to model spatial availability patterns across the
        entire city. Results were aggregated to Traffic Analysis Zones (TAZ) to enable structured
        neighborhood-level comparison and expose supply-demand mismatches that raw counts would obscure.
      </p>
      <p>
        The analysis of Quarter 7 — one of the city's more peripheral and socioeconomically mixed
        quarters — revealed a pronounced deficit: despite significant trip origin activity in the area,
        vehicle availability was substantially lower than in central quarters at equivalent demand levels.
        This evidence base directly supported arguments for redistribution requirements in operator
        licensing discussions.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="proj-section">
    <h2 class="proj-section-title">Maps — Quarter 7 Distribution Analysis</h2>
    <div class="proj-map-grid">
      <div>
        <img
          src={`${base}/maps/scooter-kde-density.png`}
          alt="Kernel density map of shared e-scooter availability in Quarter 7, Tel Aviv"
          class="proj-map"
          loading="lazy"
        />
        <p class="proj-map-caption">KDE surface — vehicle availability density across Quarter 7.</p>
      </div>
      <div>
        <img
          src={`${base}/maps/scooter-kde-taz.png`}
          alt="TAZ-level vehicle count map for Quarter 7, Tel Aviv"
          class="proj-map"
          loading="lazy"
        />
        <p class="proj-map-caption">Vehicle counts aggregated to Traffic Analysis Zones (TAZ).</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="proj-section">
    <h2 class="proj-section-title">Methods</h2>
    <div class="proj-body">
      <p>
        Vehicle location data was processed from raw Populus status-change feeds into time-stamped
        availability snapshots. SciPy's Gaussian KDE was applied to vehicle coordinates to generate a
        continuous density surface, using bandwidth selected via cross-validation to balance
        smoothing against spatial resolution.
      </p>
      <p>
        Density surfaces were rasterized and intersected with TAZ boundaries using GeoPandas spatial
        joins, enabling zonal statistics by planning area. A demand proxy — trip origin density from
        the same period — was computed in parallel and compared with availability density to derive
        a supply-demand ratio per TAZ. QGIS was used for symbology, classification, and final map output.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

</ProjectLayout>
